{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 271 "3.  Fundamental Theorem of Algebra.  The Fundamental Theorem o
f Algebra asserts that every non-constant polynomial (with complex-val
ued coefficients) has a root (a zero, a solution).  A consequence of t
he Fundamental Theorem of Algebra is that every polynomial of degree \+
" }{TEXT 270 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 13 " has exactly " }{TEXT 271 1 "n" }
{TEXT -1 108 " roots.  An alternate formulation of this consequence wo
uld be that every non-constant polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 273 1 "n
" }{TEXT -1 38 " can be factored into a product of a  " }{TEXT 272 1 "
n" }{TEXT -1 16 " linear factors." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "Consider the following polynomials:" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 6 "I.    " }
{XPPEDIT 19 1 "f := x^3-x^2-2*x" "6#>%\"fG,(*$%\"xG\"\"$\"\"\"*$F'\"\"
#!\"\"*&F+F)F'F)F," }{TEXT -1 15 "         II.   " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "g :
= 6*x^3+11*x^2+6*x+1" "6#>%\"gG,**&\"\"'\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"$F(F(*&\"#6F(
*$F*\"\"#F(F(*&F'F(F*F(F(F(F(" }{TEXT -1 24 "                 III.   \+
" }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "h := x^3-5*x+x^2-5;" "6#>%\"hG,**$%\"xG\"\"$\"\"\"*&
\"\"&F)F'F)!\"\"*$F'\"\"#F)F+F," }{TEXT -1 19 "                   " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 7 "IV.    " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "F := x^4-144" "6#
>%\"FG,&*$%\"xG\"\"%\"\"\"\"$W\"!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 19 "             V.  \+
  " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "G := 3*x^4+4*x^3-2*x^2+x-6;" "6#>%\"GG,,*&\"\"$\"
\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"%F(F(*&F+F(*$F*F'F(F(*&\"\"#F(*$F*F/F(!\"\"F*F(\"\"'F1
" }{TEXT -1 15 "         VI.   " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "H := x^5-x^2-2*x" "6#
>%\"HG,(*$%\"xG\"\"&\"\"\"*$F'\"\"#!\"\"*&F+F)F'F)F," }{TEXT -1 24 "  \+
                      " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 257 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 172 "Factor each polynomial and determine whether Mapl
e was able to find enough linear factors to demonstrate the above asse
rtion about the appropriate number of linear factors." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 24 "g:='6*x^3
+11*x^2+6*x+1':" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 19 "h:='x^3-
5*x+x^2-5':" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "F:='x^4-144':" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "G:='3*x^4+4*x^3-2*x^2+x-6':
" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "H:='x^5-x^2-2*x':" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "f:='x^3-x^2-2*x':" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 20 "factor(x^3-x^2-2*x);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%\"xG\"\"\",&F$F%F%F%F%,&F$F%\"\"#!
\"\"F%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 27 "factor(6*
x^3+11*x^2+6*x+1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&*&\"\"#\"\"
\"%\"xGF'F'F'F'F',&*&\"\"$F'F(F'F'F'F'F',&F(F'F'F'F'" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 
0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 22 "factor(x^3-5*x+x^2-5);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "
" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "factor(x^4-144);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7!\"\"F),&F%F)F*
F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 30 "factor(3*x^4+4*x^3-
2*x^2+x-6);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"\"\"#F&F
&,&F%F&F&!\"\"F&,(*&\"\"$F&)F%F'F&F&F%F&F,F&F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 20 "factor(x^5-x^2-2*x);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%\"xG\"\"\",&F$F%F%F%F%,**$)F$\"\"$F%F%*$)F$\"\"#F%!
\"\"F$F%F-F.F%" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "In those cases where \+
Maple did not find enough linear factors, there is a reason why Maple \+
did not.  Maple makes an assumption that if the coefficients of a poly
nomial are all given exactly (as integers or rational numbers [ratios \+
of integer]), then you are only interested in finding exact factors (f
actors where the coefficients are integers or rational numbers).  The \+
Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that the factors of  \+
a polynomial will necessarily have the same kind of coefficients as th
e polynomial, only the polynomial can be factored.  You can force Mapl
e to report additional (approximate) factors.  For example,  compare:
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F
&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6
#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#F&F&,&F%F&F'!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "What is t
he difference?  The extra-term is called a " }{TEXT 274 18 "field exte
nsion.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells Maple to consider additonal f
actors where the coefficients are allowed to include elements from the
 field extension.  It is fairly clear from the factoriztion of " }
{TEXT 275 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself that something involving
  sqrt(5)  would have to be included.  However, there are problems whe
re there is not a obvious clue as to which specific field extension sh
ould be added.  If you are willing to accept an appropriate solution, \+
then using the field extension " }{TEXT 276 4 "real" }{TEXT -1 179 " t
ells Maple to factor the polynomial using a floating point approximati
on scheme.  For example, consider (here I am pretending I don't see th
at adding  sqrt(5) would be optimal):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "
" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F
&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,real);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F&F&,&F%F&
$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, the Fundamental Theorem of A
lgebra does not guarantee that a polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 277 1 "
n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }{TEXT 278 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 " real lin
ear factors.  Rather, only hat it will have " }{TEXT 279 1 "n" }{TEXT 
-1 134 " linear factors.  What is the difference?  Some of the factors
 may involve complex roots rather than real roots.  For example compar
e:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&*$)
%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7!\"\"F),&F%F)F*F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,sqrt(3));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
"6#*(,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7F)F),&F'F)*&F(F)\"\"$#F)F(F)F),&F'F)*&
F(F)F-F.!\"\"F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(F
,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+:;5kM!\"
*F&F&,&F%F&$\"+:;5kMF)!\"\"F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&$\"+++++7!\")F&F&" }}}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,complex);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#**,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+:;5kM!\"*F&F&,&F%F&^#F'F&
F&,&F%F&^#$!+:;5kMF)F&F&,&F%F&$\"+:;5kMF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 126 "For the following polyno
mials demonstrate that each can be factored completely into linear fac
tors.  Use the field extensions " }{TEXT 280 4 "real" }{TEXT -1 5 " an
d " }{TEXT 281 7 "complex" }{TEXT -1 36 " only if non-rational factors
 occur." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 7 
" V.    " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "G := 3*x^4+4*x^3-2*x^2+x-6;" "6#>%\"GG,,*&\"
\"$\"\"\"*$%\"xG\"\"%F(F(*&F+F(*$F*F'F(F(*&\"\"#F(*$F*F/F(!\"\"F*F(\"
\"'F1" }{TEXT -1 15 "         VI.   " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 "H := x^5-x^2-2*x
" "6#>%\"HG,(*$%\"xG\"\"&\"\"\"*$F'\"\"#!\"\"*&F+F)F'F)F," }{TEXT -1 
10 "          " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 7 "VII.   " }{XPPEDIT 19 1 
