+++++5!\"*F(F*F(F1$F;F<F(F(F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A rela
ted theorem about finding roots of polynomials (equivalently factoring
 polynomials into a product of linear factors) asserts that if the pol
ynomial has real coefficients -- all of the polynomials we have consid
ered (and will consider) have had real coefficients -- then any comple
x roots (or factors) must occur in conjugate pairs.  For example, both
 the complex factors of " }{TEXT 282 5 "F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }
{TEXT 283 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 236 "(above) all occurred in conjugate pair
s.  Demonstrate this theorem by creating three new polynomials, name t
hem F1, G1 and H1, of degree 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show that the any \+
complex factors of F1, G1 and H1 occur in conjugate pairs." }}{EXCHG 
